**c.** A cash break-even is defined as the point where in the operational cash flow is equal to zero. 

In order to solve the cash break-even point, we will use the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC}}{\text{P}-\text{v}}
\end{aligned}$$

where,
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{FC}&=\text{Fixed costs}\\
\text{P}&=\text{Price per unit}\\
\text{v}&=\text{Variable cost per unit}
\end{aligned}$$

Accounting break-even refers to the point where in the net income is actually equal to zero given the depreciation value.

To solve this, we will use the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC}+\text{D}}{\text{P}-\text{v}}
\end{aligned}$$

where,
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{FC}&=\text{Fixed costs}\\
\text{D}&=\text{Depreciation}\\
\text{P}&=\text{Price per unit}\\
\text{v}&=\text{Variable cost per unit}
\end{aligned}$$
